class Solution {
public:
    int minOrAfterOperations(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int ans=0;
        int mask=0; // used for performing operation on prefix of bits
        for(int j=30;j>=0;j--){ // builds answer bit by bit
            mask=mask | (1<<j);// mask changes(10000.. -> 11000..->11100..->11110..->111111..)

            int cosecutiveAnd=mask;
            int mergeCount=0;// no. of merges required to make current bit 0
            for(int i:nums){
                cosecutiveAnd = cosecutiveAnd & i; 
                if((cosecutiveAnd|ans)!=ans) // explained below
                    mergeCount++; //while above condition is not achieved keep merging
                else cosecutiveAnd=mask; // else reset cosecutiveAnd to mask(11111..0000...), no need to increase count
            }

            if(mergeCount>k)
                ans|=(1<<j);// if(count is more than k, make set curent bit of 1, else it stays 0)
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Let us go through above code in details-

mask=mask | (1<<j);
Here we see that mask is being shifted to the right j positions from LSB position of the given number. So if we get any one set bit of the given number(for example 8, after mask operation 11000...), now when we shift it to the right j position we get 1000.. in 32 position. So mask becomes 11000..10000.. in every iteration.

cosecutiveAnd=cosecutiveAnd & i;
This means if any consecutive bits of 1 in the mask become 0 by doing 1 AND with the given number, we need to merge it back(because the number was already merged for this particular mask in the previous step). So we keep a counter and add 1 to it when we find any consecutive 1 bits in the mask. If we don't find any consecutive 1 bits, we reset the counter to 0.

ans|=(1<<j);
This is the final step where we check if we have merged enough bits to make the current bit 0. If we have not, we keep adding 1 to the counter and finally set the current bit to 0.

This is the key idea behind the above code. We are essentially performing operations on the prefix of bits of the given number. We use a mask to shift the bits to the right and merge the bits that are already merged. We keep doing this until we have merged enough bits to make the current bit 0. Finally, we check if we have merged enough bits and set the current bit to 0 if we haven't.

The time complexity of the above code is O(n log n) because we are doing a binary search in the array. The space complexity is O(1) because we are not using any extra space except for the mask variable. The above code can be modified to return the result as an integer by using a loop to iterate through the array and perform the operations on each element.
